+            /*
+             * KVM/Tahoe (xnu-12377) EL0 (userland) DEBUG-EXCEPTION ROOT FIX
+             * (2026-06-16). Sibling of [mdscr-kde]/[mlsie-debug] above; this is
+             * the one that stops launchd-critical daemons (kernelmanagerd, ...)
+             * from being KILLED by a spurious EL0 SIGTRAP.
+             *
+             * SYMPTOM (live on the SET-UP disk under KVM): kernelmanagerd is
+             * respawned repeatedly (pid 121 -> 206 -> 209 ...); each instance has
+             * a thread that "triggered fail-safe by spinning for at least
+             * 1000000us at fixed priority" then "exited -- exit reason namespace 2
+             * subcode 0x5" (= SIGTRAP). The kernel also logs "triggered unnest of
+             * range ... of DYLD shared region ... While not abnormal for
+             * debuggers" -- the tell-tale of a single-step/monitor-debug storm at
+             * EL0. kernelmanagerd is launchd-critical, so its death panics the box.
+             *
+             * ROOT: the host (Neoverse-N3) ID_AA64DFR0_EL1.DoubleLock = 0xf is
+             * NOT spoofable by KVM, so XNU can never engage the OS debug lock; an
+             * EL0 debug-enable bit (MDSCR_EL1.SS single-step / .MDE monitor-debug)
+             * gets armed and the resulting debug exception is delivered to the
+             * daemon as EXC_BREAKPOINT -> SIGTRAP, in a self-perpetuating storm.
+             * [mdscr-kde] only stopped the EL1 KDE bit; EL0 SS/MDE are armed via a
+             * DIFFERENT path (the per-thread debug-state setter), so daemons still
+             * die.
+             *
+             * THE CHOKEPOINT: every MDSCR_EL1 modification in XNU routes through one
+             * read-modify-write helper update_mdscr(clear_x0, set_x1):
+             *     mov  x17, #0x0            ; d2800011
+             *     mrs  x16, mdscr_el1       ; d5300250
+             *     bic  x16, x16, x0         ; 8a200210   (clear caller's x0 bits)
+             *     orr  x16, x16, x1         ; aa010210   (SET caller's x1 bits) <== NOP
+             *     and  x16, x16, #~KDE      ; 9272fa10   (force-clear bit13 KDE)
+             *     msr  mdscr_el1, x16       ; d5100250
+             *     tst  x16, #0x2000         ; f273021f
+             * The per-thread debug-state setter (arm_debug_set_state) arms EL0
+             * single-step by calling update_mdscr(0, 0x1) (set SS=bit0); it also
+             * sets/clears MDE(bit15) the same way. By NOPing the `orr x16,x16,x1`
+             * the helper can no longer SET any MDSCR bit -> SS and MDE can NEVER be
+             * armed (the disarm calls via `bic` still work; the existing AND keeps
+             * KDE clear). EL0 debug exceptions are therefore never raised on ANY
+             * thread -> no daemon takes a spurious SIGTRAP. This is a ROOT fix (one
+             * chokepoint covers every daemon), not a per-daemon workaround.
+             *
+             * Anchored on the full 7-word slide-invariant window (all register-
+             * relative, no PC-relative operands) -> UNIQUE in the kernelcache
+             * (verified: exactly 1 occurrence in a live pmemsave of the loaded
+             * set-up-disk kernelcache, VA 0xfffffe0022cf51e4). The `orr` is at +0xc.
+             * KVM-only: under TCG/HVF apple-gxf engages the OS double lock so EL0
+             * debug is harmless and the guest must keep the live helper. Non-
+             * latching: once NOP'd the window no longer matches; multiple KC copies
+             * are each cleaned.
